1
00:03:47,492 --> 00:03:48,618
Move it up.

2
00:03:48,994 --> 00:03:50,537
- Is this right?
- Yes.

3
00:03:59,880 --> 00:04:03,174
- We're not supposed to take these.
- Don't worry about it.

4
00:04:03,633 --> 00:04:06,303
- Just get the net in.
- I don't think you're....

5
00:04:08,763 --> 00:04:09,806
Jesus.

6
00:04:20,650 --> 00:04:22,819
We're not pulling at the same time.

7
00:04:26,448 --> 00:04:29,034
What? Jesus!

8
00:04:56,478 --> 00:04:59,814
Did any more of you guys see Carl
at Ship Channel Bank last night?

9
00:04:59,898 --> 00:05:02,859
- Why do you want to know?
- To see if somebody talked to him.

10
00:05:02,942 --> 00:05:05,862
Fish went sour when the fog rolled in.
I got out of there.

11
00:05:05,945 --> 00:05:08,656
We got Ferry, Hardwell,
Moulton, Miyamoto.

12
00:05:08,782 --> 00:05:10,700
- Anybody else?
- Japs.

13
00:05:12,702 --> 00:05:14,871
I figured you'd have heard by now.

14
00:05:16,039 --> 00:05:17,332
All right...

15
00:05:17,749 --> 00:05:22,253
- ... if you see any of these guys...
- Art's starting to sound like a real sheriff.

16
00:05:22,921 --> 00:05:27,384
- Do think this was just an accident?
- Of course it is, but a man's dead, William.

17
00:05:27,801 --> 00:05:30,428
I've gotta write my report.
God, I hate this.

18
00:05:31,805 --> 00:05:33,723
Chambers, tell me...

19
00:05:34,057 --> 00:05:38,686
...I'm not gonna get your newspaper and
see an article about an investigation, am I?

20
00:05:38,812 --> 00:05:42,649
- You want me to lie?
- No, I want to be off the record.

21
00:05:42,816 --> 00:05:44,317
That's what I want.

22
00:05:47,320 --> 00:05:51,491
I mean, if there is a killer,
why would you want him all alerted?

23
00:05:51,783 --> 00:05:54,994
- So there's a murder investigation?
- I didn't say that.

24
00:07:59,035 --> 00:08:01,204
Hatsue? You all right?

25
00:08:02,705 --> 00:08:04,374
Go away, Ishmael.

26
00:08:11,839 --> 00:08:14,425
- Look, I just wanted to tell you...
- Go away.

27
00:08:27,522 --> 00:08:29,232
There you go, Miyamoto.

28
00:08:41,953 --> 00:08:43,913
Just a minute.

29
00:08:50,753 --> 00:08:52,130
Morning, Kazuo.

30
00:08:53,506 --> 00:08:55,675
I've come to get you out of here.

31
00:08:58,719 --> 00:09:00,221
Good morning, sir.

32
00:09:00,471 --> 00:09:01,931
Counselor.

33
00:09:04,642 --> 00:09:05,935
Sorry I'm late.

34
00:09:06,185 --> 00:09:07,603
That's all right.

35
00:09:07,687 --> 00:09:09,856
Looks like we have a good turnout.

36
00:09:19,740 --> 00:09:22,368
How about that jury?
What a bunch of yokels.

37
00:09:23,661 --> 00:09:25,788
Have you seen this Island Review rag?

38
00:09:25,872 --> 00:09:29,417
Guy writes like this trial is
the biggest thing ever happened.

39
00:09:29,584 --> 00:09:33,504
- Why is this news in Seattle?
- Because he's a Jap. Simple as that.

40
00:09:36,674 --> 00:09:38,259
Take a look at that.

41
00:10:33,648 --> 00:10:35,983
Would you tell us, please, Sheriff...

42
00:10:36,400 --> 00:10:38,653
...what was your first impression...

43
00:10:38,778 --> 00:10:43,824
...as you and your deputy inspected
the Susan Marie that September morning?

44
00:10:45,409 --> 00:10:46,702
Mainly...

45
00:10:46,869 --> 00:10:48,955
...how quiet it was out there...

46
00:10:50,665 --> 00:10:52,625
...things just didn't add up.

47
00:10:54,085 --> 00:10:57,713
- "Add up?" What do you mean?
- Fishermen drown. It happens.

48
00:10:58,714 --> 00:11:00,633
But Carl Heine....

49
00:11:00,883 --> 00:11:03,594
I got to thinking, he was so meticulous.

50
00:11:04,387 --> 00:11:06,514
He did everything right by the darn book.

51
00:11:07,264 --> 00:11:10,768
Every single light is on and his net's out.

52
00:11:12,186 --> 00:11:15,356
- I got a bad feeling about this.
- Don't say that, Abel.

53
00:11:15,564 --> 00:11:17,775
Don't even think like that. Jesus.

54
00:12:31,599 --> 00:12:33,601
There's nothing in the hold...

55
00:12:33,934 --> 00:12:35,436
...apart from fish.

56
00:12:36,312 --> 00:12:38,105
You wanna pull up the net?

57
00:12:39,064 --> 00:12:42,985
So looking at the evidence there
you determined this was no accident.

58
00:12:46,572 --> 00:12:49,033
I didn't determine
much of anything at first.

59
00:12:49,116 --> 00:12:52,411
I just kept wondering what
I was gonna say to his family.

60
00:12:52,536 --> 00:12:54,330
After all, I knew the guy.

61
00:12:54,955 --> 00:12:56,790
I knew his wife and children and....

62
00:13:19,813 --> 00:13:21,857
- Hey, men.
- Hi.

63
00:13:23,859 --> 00:13:26,820
- Is your mother home?
- She's inside.

64
00:13:28,739 --> 00:13:30,241
Go on and play now.

65
00:13:31,450 --> 00:13:33,202
She's right in there.

66
00:13:42,586 --> 00:13:43,963
Susan Marie?

67
00:13:44,922 --> 00:13:47,716
Come in! I'll be right down!

68
00:14:05,985 --> 00:14:07,569
What can I do for you?

69
00:14:07,820 --> 00:14:10,239
- Carl's not home yet.
- That's what I....

70
00:14:13,367 --> 00:14:14,910
That's why I'm here.

71
00:14:18,122 --> 00:14:21,125
I'm afraid I've got
some very bad news to tell you.

72
00:14:21,750 --> 00:14:23,460
The worst kind of news.

73
00:14:26,130 --> 00:14:29,633
Carl died last night
out at Ship Channel Bank.

74
00:14:33,345 --> 00:14:35,305
Carl's just fine.

75
00:14:37,808 --> 00:14:39,643
I found him, Susan Marie.

76
00:14:40,144 --> 00:14:42,187
I found him tangled in his net.

77
00:14:50,779 --> 00:14:52,531
I knew this would happen.

78
00:15:00,205 --> 00:15:01,915
I warned him.

79
00:15:24,646 --> 00:15:28,192
You said there was no sign of a struggle.

80
00:15:28,525 --> 00:15:30,444
Nothing out of the ordinary.

81
00:15:36,200 --> 00:15:39,369
As I said, with a fella as particular as Carl...

82
00:15:40,037 --> 00:15:42,498
...there were a few things
that struck me as odd.

83
00:15:42,581 --> 00:15:45,876
You mentioned the coffee cup on the floor.

84
00:15:47,002 --> 00:15:50,214
Was there anything else out of place?

85
00:15:51,006 --> 00:15:53,884
There was a dead battery
just lying around and...

86
00:15:54,092 --> 00:15:57,012
...the cover to the battery well
didn't fit right.

87
00:15:57,930 --> 00:16:00,516
A battery cover that didn't fit.

88
00:16:01,975 --> 00:16:03,560
What did you make of that?

89
00:16:03,644 --> 00:16:06,396
Objection. Asking the witness
to speculate.

90
00:16:07,689 --> 00:16:11,818
Was I supposed to object every time
you did that?

91
00:16:12,319 --> 00:16:15,405
That's quite enough horseplay.
Try and act your age.

92
00:16:15,697 --> 00:16:18,116
If I did that, Your Honor, I'd be dead.

93
00:16:19,201 --> 00:16:22,496
- Proceed, gentlemen.
- There's an objection, Your Honor.

94
00:16:23,080 --> 00:16:24,581
And it's overruled.

95
00:16:25,082 --> 00:16:27,000
You may answer the question.

96
00:16:27,918 --> 00:16:32,089
I looked under the lid and one
of the batteries was bigger than the other.

97
00:16:33,340 --> 00:16:35,550
Didn't that also strike you as odd...

98
00:16:35,634 --> 00:16:40,180
...that he would have a battery that
didn't fit, a man as particular as Carl?

99
00:16:41,098 --> 00:16:42,933
Yeah, I wondered.

100
00:16:43,517 --> 00:16:46,770
But he'd done some
on-the-spot work, you see.

101
00:16:46,853 --> 00:16:49,231
And the flange was kind of...

102
00:16:49,856 --> 00:16:53,318
...banged away to make room
for the one that was too big.

103
00:16:53,402 --> 00:16:57,239
Would this "too big" battery have fit, say...

104
00:16:57,781 --> 00:16:59,741
...in Kazuo Miyamoto's battery well?

105
00:17:00,409 --> 00:17:03,745
It was the exact same type as Miyamoto's,
that's for sure, but...

106
00:17:04,413 --> 00:17:08,959
...he had both of his batteries in
when we searched his boat later on, so....

107
00:17:30,939 --> 00:17:33,817
Ifyou fall off a motorcycle,
the injuries look different.

108
00:17:33,900 --> 00:17:39,281
In this case, the injury had been inflicted
by a long, narrow, flat object.

109
00:17:40,157 --> 00:17:43,493
- Like a fishing gaff, for example?
- That's very possible.

110
00:17:47,205 --> 00:17:51,168
You say it was a laceration about
two and a half inches long...

111
00:17:51,501 --> 00:17:53,295
...over the left ear.

112
00:17:54,087 --> 00:17:58,049
The bone under it
fractured over a four-inch area.

113
00:17:58,133 --> 00:17:59,926
What would've caused that?

114
00:18:00,051 --> 00:18:03,597
I'll tell you what a head wound like this
puts me in mind of.

115
00:18:03,972 --> 00:18:07,726
I've seen wounds exactly like this...

116
00:18:07,851 --> 00:18:10,687
...many times in the war.

117
00:18:10,854 --> 00:18:13,857
Have you seen this specific kind
of wound before?

118
00:18:13,940 --> 00:18:17,569
Frequently, as a result
of hand-to-hand combat with Jap soldiers.

119
00:18:17,652 --> 00:18:18,904
I even told Art:

120
00:18:18,987 --> 00:18:23,533
"You wanna play Sherlock Holmes,
look for a Jap with a bloody gun butt."

121
00:18:24,159 --> 00:18:26,161
What led you to that conclusion?

122
00:18:26,244 --> 00:18:31,082
I've seen these kendo wounds many times,
exactly like this one.

123
00:18:31,249 --> 00:18:33,710
Could you tell us what kendo is?

124
00:18:45,222 --> 00:18:47,474
Kendo is Japanese stick fighting.

125
00:18:47,599 --> 00:18:51,061
They train as kids, you know,
to kill with sticks.

126
00:18:57,442 --> 00:18:59,611
No further questions. Thank you.

127
00:19:36,898 --> 00:19:39,693
Your report states
it was death by drowning...

128
00:19:40,485 --> 00:19:42,028
...not a kendo wound.

129
00:19:42,487 --> 00:19:43,989
How did you determine this?

130
00:19:44,072 --> 00:19:48,994
As I've already testified,
I found foam in the deceased's lungs.

131
00:19:50,036 --> 00:19:51,413
This foam.

132
00:19:51,830 --> 00:19:54,457
I'm not sure I understand about this.

133
00:19:55,000 --> 00:19:56,626
What would cause that again?

134
00:19:56,710 --> 00:20:00,714
It occurs when water,
mucus and air are mixed by respiration.

135
00:20:00,964 --> 00:20:03,550
Breathing, that is. I believe I said that.

136
00:20:03,633 --> 00:20:05,635
But you can see why I'm confused.

137
00:20:05,719 --> 00:20:08,596
Because a drowned person
doesn't breathe, so...

138
00:20:08,680 --> 00:20:13,268
Of course not. The foam means
that he went in breathing.

139
00:20:13,560 --> 00:20:17,856
That's why the autopsy report shows
drowning as the cause of death.

140
00:20:18,815 --> 00:20:23,778
Meaning that he wasn't murdered first,
on the deck, then thrown overboard.

141
00:20:24,070 --> 00:20:28,324
- Well, you can always...
- Thank you. That's important, that's good.

142
00:20:28,783 --> 00:20:31,244
There's something else
I'd like to ask you about.

143
00:20:31,327 --> 00:20:33,413
Something in your report.

144
00:20:34,080 --> 00:20:36,291
Go ahead, ask.

145
00:20:36,791 --> 00:20:39,127
About the wound to the deceased's head.

146
00:20:39,210 --> 00:20:40,670
You say here...

147
00:20:40,962 --> 00:20:44,924
...that it was made
by a long, narrow, flat object.

148
00:20:45,884 --> 00:20:48,970
Is that what you saw,
or it is just your inference?

149
00:20:49,512 --> 00:20:52,724
It's my job to infer.
That's what coroners do, we infer.

150
00:20:52,807 --> 00:20:56,352
That's my area of expertise, inference.

151
00:20:56,895 --> 00:20:58,271
Of course it is.

152
00:20:59,189 --> 00:21:00,732
Can you infer, then...

153
00:21:00,815 --> 00:21:04,694
...whether an object was propelled
against the head of the deceased...

154
00:21:04,778 --> 00:21:07,447
...or if his head moved against an object...

155
00:21:07,655 --> 00:21:10,116
...or would both look the same?

156
00:21:10,575 --> 00:21:11,701
The same.

157
00:21:11,993 --> 00:21:16,623
If the head struck something narrow
and flat like the gunnel of the boat...

158
00:21:16,790 --> 00:21:20,043
...or net roller, a fairlead, could that have...

159
00:21:20,418 --> 00:21:24,214
If the head were moving fast enough,
but I don't see how it could be.

160
00:21:24,297 --> 00:21:27,383
- Nonetheless, it is possible?
- Anything's possible.

161
00:21:27,467 --> 00:21:31,054
Is it fair to say that you don't know
for certain which it was?

162
00:21:31,221 --> 00:21:32,764
Didn't I just say...

163
00:21:33,056 --> 00:21:34,724
I already said that.

164
00:21:34,974 --> 00:21:37,894
But you are certain
that he died by drowning?

165
00:21:38,102 --> 00:21:40,688
For the third time, yes.

166
00:21:41,648 --> 00:21:45,235
- Can I say something here?
- No. You've been more than helpful.

167
00:21:45,735 --> 00:21:48,780
- No further questions.
- The witness may stand down.

168
00:21:49,072 --> 00:21:52,617
We'll take our lunch recess now.
Reconvene at 1:30 sharp.

169
00:22:06,923 --> 00:22:08,049
How are the kids?

170
00:22:08,132 --> 00:22:10,510
They made a snowman
to welcome you home.

171
00:22:12,762 --> 00:22:14,347
Wow, that's great.

172
00:22:16,766 --> 00:22:18,351
Just a few more days.

173
00:22:19,102 --> 00:22:20,603
You look beautiful.

174
00:22:20,812 --> 00:22:22,814
I'm not going until you smile.

175
00:22:27,902 --> 00:22:30,488
I think it's dangerous with this jury.

176
00:26:59,423 --> 00:27:01,675
I'm sorry I kissed you on the beach.

177
00:27:07,098 --> 00:27:08,849
Let's just forget about it.

178
00:27:08,933 --> 00:27:10,434
Forget it happened.

179
00:27:11,227 --> 00:27:13,687
Don't be sorry. I'm not.

180
00:27:18,567 --> 00:27:20,069
Me neither.

181
00:27:56,355 --> 00:27:58,607
Do you think this is wrong?

182
00:28:01,318 --> 00:28:02,778
Your friends would.

183
00:28:03,487 --> 00:28:05,197
Your dad would kill me.

184
00:28:05,823 --> 00:28:08,450
My mom is the problem.

185
00:28:16,125 --> 00:28:18,377
Stay away from white boys.

186
00:28:19,128 --> 00:28:23,674
Marry one of your own kind
whose heart is strong and gentle.

187
00:28:25,843 --> 00:28:29,930
The hairpin should be better placed
for a girl to find the right husband.

188
00:28:32,850 --> 00:28:35,477
She teaches me to be Japanese.

189
00:28:36,103 --> 00:28:37,396
What does that mean?

190
00:28:37,479 --> 00:28:40,566
Dances, calligraphy, how to do my hair...

191
00:28:40,983 --> 00:28:42,860
...how to sit without moving.

192
00:28:43,611 --> 00:28:45,404
What's the point of that?

193
00:28:48,824 --> 00:28:50,492
It's a part of grace.

194
00:28:50,784 --> 00:28:53,037
You boys don't understand.

195
00:28:53,662 --> 00:28:55,122
Try me.

196
00:28:57,458 --> 00:29:00,210
She doesn't let me get away with anything.

197
00:29:02,004 --> 00:29:03,631
It's the same for me.

198
00:29:04,131 --> 00:29:05,591
Except it's my dad.

199
00:29:30,407 --> 00:29:34,745
Know what would happen to an operator
who got his sleeve caught in the press?

200
00:29:35,329 --> 00:29:36,580
Do you?

201
00:29:36,914 --> 00:29:41,126
He'd be popped open like a balloon,
splattered all over the walls.

202
00:29:44,463 --> 00:29:46,632
Even his bones would disappear...

203
00:29:47,341 --> 00:29:51,387
...to be discovered later on the floor
like strips of white confetti.

204
00:29:55,933 --> 00:29:58,852
We'll make a newspaperman
out of you yet.

205
00:32:04,519 --> 00:32:05,771
James!

206
00:32:24,748 --> 00:32:28,335
Ever wonder why the Strawberry Princess
is always a Japanese girl?

207
00:32:28,418 --> 00:32:31,838
- Not really.
- Your father will explain it to you anyway.

208
00:32:31,963 --> 00:32:34,716
It's sort of an unwitting virgin sacrifice.

209
00:32:34,925 --> 00:32:37,469
A concept of racial harmony, you know...

210
00:32:37,678 --> 00:32:39,930
...and for a while it seems to work.

211
00:32:47,562 --> 00:32:51,024
- That's the Fajita girl, isn't it?
- No, that's Hatsue Imada.

212
00:32:51,274 --> 00:32:52,859
Yes, she's lovely.

213
00:33:14,548 --> 00:33:16,299
Mrs. Heine...

214
00:33:17,134 --> 00:33:18,343
...you were...

215
00:33:18,802 --> 00:33:23,306
...acquainted with the defendant
and his family, were you not?

216
00:33:24,057 --> 00:33:26,560
Him and his folks worked our land.

217
00:33:27,310 --> 00:33:29,855
They lived in one of our cabins at first.

218
00:33:30,313 --> 00:33:34,818
So, the defendant knew the deceased,
your son, even then?

219
00:33:38,780 --> 00:33:40,365
They fished together.

220
00:33:41,616 --> 00:33:43,160
They went to school.

221
00:33:43,493 --> 00:33:46,204
My boy Carl treated him
like a white person...

222
00:33:47,164 --> 00:33:49,249
...just like any friend.

223
00:33:50,750 --> 00:33:55,589
So tell us, Mrs. Heine,
where did things go wrong?

224
00:34:01,386 --> 00:34:03,430
My husband went and sold...

225
00:34:05,599 --> 00:34:08,059
...his father seven acres of our land.

226
00:34:08,518 --> 00:34:11,146
That fence to that fence
and then down to the road.

227
00:34:11,229 --> 00:34:13,648
- That's seven acres, yes?
- No.

228
00:34:13,899 --> 00:34:16,318
Where, to the edge of the mountain?

229
00:34:27,162 --> 00:34:30,040
All right. You drive a hard bargain.

230
00:34:32,751 --> 00:34:35,337
And that's where all this trouble started.

231
00:34:35,670 --> 00:34:37,422
But how can this be?

232
00:34:38,757 --> 00:34:40,717
Since we all know...

233
00:34:40,884 --> 00:34:44,638
...that it is against the law
for Japanese-born to own land?

234
00:34:45,931 --> 00:34:47,891
Even leasing is illegal.

235
00:34:48,350 --> 00:34:51,186
So what was the point
of this payment plan?

236
00:34:51,353 --> 00:34:54,898
Their kids were born here.
So, when the oldest...

237
00:34:56,441 --> 00:34:57,984
...that one there...

238
00:34:58,234 --> 00:35:01,363
...was 20 and the last payment got made...

239
00:35:01,696 --> 00:35:03,073
...he could own it.

240
00:35:03,156 --> 00:35:05,742
But they missed their last two payments...

241
00:35:06,201 --> 00:35:07,661
...so that was that.

242
00:35:07,744 --> 00:35:10,664
They missed their last two payments...

243
00:35:11,331 --> 00:35:13,500
...after years of not missing one?

244
00:35:14,292 --> 00:35:16,836
It was the war. They were gone.

245
00:35:17,754 --> 00:35:21,716
They were sent off to the camps
with all the other Japs.

246
00:35:23,218 --> 00:35:26,763
We must leave everything.
If you like, work our fields.

247
00:35:26,846 --> 00:35:28,598
Sell berries, keep money.

248
00:35:28,765 --> 00:35:30,392
Otherwise they will rot.

249
00:35:31,309 --> 00:35:34,354
- Today I have half money for next payment.
- Absolutely not.

250
00:35:34,437 --> 00:35:36,898
I'm not going to take your savings.

251
00:35:37,524 --> 00:35:38,775
You take the money.

252
00:35:38,858 --> 00:35:41,528
$125. I will send more
from where I'm going.

253
00:35:41,611 --> 00:35:44,698
If it's not enough, sell my seven acres
and keep the money.

254
00:35:44,781 --> 00:35:46,950
I thought you were giving us those.

255
00:35:48,993 --> 00:35:53,081
Didn't you come in here giving them away?
Now you want to make up the other half...

256
00:35:53,164 --> 00:35:55,834
...in berries you expect us
to tend and pick?

257
00:35:55,917 --> 00:35:58,294
Is that what you come here hoping for?

258
00:36:00,797 --> 00:36:02,632
You want more coffee?

259
00:36:03,133 --> 00:36:04,509
No, thank you.

260
00:36:05,051 --> 00:36:07,554
- Take the money.
- Etta has been rude to you.

261
00:36:08,555 --> 00:36:10,432
For that, I apologize.

262
00:36:11,766 --> 00:36:13,226
Keep this money.

263
00:36:14,978 --> 00:36:16,646
Those payments will work out....

264
00:36:16,730 --> 00:36:19,399
The arrangement was,
those payments would be made...

265
00:36:20,316 --> 00:36:21,901
...somewhere down the road.

266
00:36:23,278 --> 00:36:25,864
The road ended
when my husband passed away.

267
00:36:26,448 --> 00:36:28,658
I couldn't run the farm by myself...

268
00:36:29,117 --> 00:36:30,326
...so I...

269
00:36:30,910 --> 00:36:34,038
...sold all 30 acres to Ole Jurgensen.

270
00:36:35,415 --> 00:36:37,375
And for a fair price this time.

271
00:36:38,751 --> 00:36:40,628
And I sent back their equity...

272
00:36:40,712 --> 00:36:42,881
...to those Japs down to that camp...

273
00:36:43,131 --> 00:36:45,925
...in California, which I didn't have to do.

274
00:36:46,801 --> 00:36:48,970
So they got all their money back?

275
00:36:49,304 --> 00:36:50,597
That was that.

276
00:36:51,806 --> 00:36:54,017
Did you hear from
the defendant's family again?

277
00:36:54,100 --> 00:36:57,187
Yes, I heard from them.
I heard from that one there.

278
00:36:57,270 --> 00:37:00,440
That one sitting there
just showed up at my door.

279
00:37:04,903 --> 00:37:07,697
Carl's overseas. He's fighting the Japs.

280
00:37:08,823 --> 00:37:11,826
- What is it you want?
- I came to get our land back.

281
00:37:12,202 --> 00:37:13,620
It isn't yours.

282
00:37:13,745 --> 00:37:16,789
- It's Ole Jurgensen's now. Talk to him.
- I just did.

283
00:37:17,540 --> 00:37:20,919
He didn't know it was ours.
You didn't tell him it was promised...

284
00:37:21,002 --> 00:37:24,547
I'm supposed to tell him there's
an illegal contract muddling things up?

285
00:37:24,631 --> 00:37:26,841
You people didn't make your payments.

286
00:37:26,925 --> 00:37:29,594
In America, the bank comes in
and repossesses your land.

287
00:37:29,677 --> 00:37:32,388
- I didn't do anything wrong.
- Nothing illegal.

288
00:37:32,555 --> 00:37:34,140
Wrong is a different matter.

289
00:37:34,224 --> 00:37:35,141
Get out!

290
00:37:35,225 --> 00:37:37,560
You took advantage of the fact
that we were gone!

291
00:37:37,644 --> 00:37:41,231
You sold the land from under us
while I was fighting the Nazis!

292
00:40:06,709 --> 00:40:07,919
Your witness.

293
00:40:13,174 --> 00:40:14,967
Just three questions.

294
00:40:16,844 --> 00:40:19,972
The Miyamoto family
bought your seven acres...

295
00:40:21,015 --> 00:40:22,725
...for $4,500?

296
00:40:23,518 --> 00:40:26,354
They tried to.
They defaulted on their payments.

297
00:40:27,188 --> 00:40:28,564
Second question:

298
00:40:28,814 --> 00:40:31,400
What did Ole Jurgensen pay you per acre?

299
00:40:31,984 --> 00:40:33,402
$1,000.

300
00:40:34,070 --> 00:40:35,321
I guess...

301
00:40:36,072 --> 00:40:41,285
...that makes what would have been
$4,500 into $7,000, doesn't it?

302
00:40:41,577 --> 00:40:43,746
So if you sent the equity back...

303
00:40:43,871 --> 00:40:47,041
...you had a profit of $2,500?

304
00:40:48,167 --> 00:40:50,086
Is that your third question?

305
00:40:50,378 --> 00:40:51,671
It is.

306
00:40:52,004 --> 00:40:54,006
You've done your math right.

307
00:40:54,882 --> 00:40:56,676
You too, Mrs. Heine.

308
00:40:57,677 --> 00:40:59,136
No further questions.

309
00:40:59,220 --> 00:41:00,680
You may step down.

310
00:41:02,014 --> 00:41:05,268
Before we adjourn for the day,
there's one more thing.

311
00:41:08,396 --> 00:41:10,690
This court takes judicial notice of the fact...

312
00:41:10,773 --> 00:41:14,944
...that tomorrow is the ninth anniversary
of the attack on Pearl Harbor...

313
00:41:15,069 --> 00:41:18,197
...which has no relationship
whatsoever to this trial.

314
00:41:19,824 --> 00:41:21,742
Which is why I mention it.

315
00:41:24,412 --> 00:41:26,038
9:30 tomorrow morning.

316
00:41:26,497 --> 00:41:27,873
Stay warm.

317
00:41:30,376 --> 00:41:33,754
They plowed clear out to the point.
What's the big attraction?

318
00:41:33,838 --> 00:41:37,842
I'm checking lighthouse records to see
if it's the biggest snowstorm in history.

319
00:41:37,925 --> 00:41:39,552
Where were you in '29?

320
00:41:39,635 --> 00:41:41,387
That was a snowstorm.

321
00:41:41,512 --> 00:41:43,681
- Real blizzard.
- Is that right?

322
00:41:43,848 --> 00:41:47,309
If you don't believe me,
check those Coast Guard records.

323
00:41:47,435 --> 00:41:49,437
There should be a story in it.

324
00:41:49,603 --> 00:41:53,232
Scribble, scribble, while the rest
of us have to work for a living.

325
00:41:53,315 --> 00:41:55,026
Always a pleasure.

326
00:42:52,708 --> 00:42:56,003
Everything's dated.
We do things by dates, mainly.

327
00:42:56,879 --> 00:43:01,383
Radio transmissions, shipping logs,
weather reports. The whole nine yards.

328
00:43:01,759 --> 00:43:03,886
Those stacks go clear back to Noah.

329
00:43:03,969 --> 00:43:06,305
Not that anyone ever pays them any mind.

330
00:43:06,388 --> 00:43:08,641
You monitor all radio activity?
Fishermen...

331
00:43:08,724 --> 00:43:10,351
- ... that sort of thing?
- Pretty much.

332
00:43:10,434 --> 00:43:14,438
Anything significant anyway.
Some of these guys never shut up.

333
00:43:14,522 --> 00:43:16,565
Well, just yell if you need me.

334
00:43:24,615 --> 00:43:26,534
Left is as good as right.

335
00:43:27,493 --> 00:43:29,036
Your move.

336
00:44:08,033 --> 00:44:10,703
"Correcting course via Ship Channel Bank.

337
00:44:15,040 --> 00:44:16,625
"S.S. West Corona...

338
00:44:16,959 --> 00:44:20,421
"... pilot relays position
somewhere off south buoy 56.

339
00:44:21,171 --> 00:44:25,759
"At 1:48 a.m., S.S. West Corona made
a corrective dogleg to the northwest.

340
00:44:25,884 --> 00:44:29,054
"Ship's navigator took
three insurance readings. "

341
00:44:53,287 --> 00:44:54,663
Hey, Levant?

342
00:44:58,083 --> 00:44:59,460
Here's the shipping channel.

343
00:44:59,543 --> 00:45:02,588
Any freighter off course
can dogleg back through here.

344
00:45:02,671 --> 00:45:06,759
- That happens if we're really socked in.
- Don't the gillnetters work off this bank?

345
00:45:06,842 --> 00:45:10,929
Not even they're crazy enough
to hang around in a bad fog. They get out.

346
00:45:12,473 --> 00:45:14,767
What's this got to do
with your snowstorm story?

347
00:45:14,850 --> 00:45:17,311
Nothing. Just curious, that's all.

348
00:45:18,979 --> 00:45:20,689
That doesn't make him guilty.

349
00:45:21,607 --> 00:45:24,777
- This island ought to be ashamed.
- It's not as simple as that.

350
00:45:25,402 --> 00:45:28,822
I followed every second of it.
The evidence sounds very solid.

351
00:45:28,906 --> 00:45:31,617
This prosecutor has his facts all lined up.

352
00:45:31,700 --> 00:45:34,119
You haven't heard the defense case yet.

353
00:45:34,787 --> 00:45:37,331
You sound as if you're ready to hang him.

354
00:45:37,873 --> 00:45:39,166
Besides...

355
00:45:39,333 --> 00:45:41,376
...you can't depend on facts...

356
00:45:41,627 --> 00:45:44,213
- ... not by themselves.
- What else is there?

357
00:45:44,797 --> 00:45:45,964
Emotions?

358
00:45:46,507 --> 00:45:49,384
Facts you can cling to.
Emotions just float away.

359
00:45:51,136 --> 00:45:52,429
Then let them.

360
00:46:13,909 --> 00:46:15,410
I love you.

361
00:46:23,418 --> 00:46:25,003
You smell like cedar.

362
00:46:26,255 --> 00:46:27,714
So do you.

363
00:47:01,081 --> 00:47:03,083
I can hear your heart beating.

364
00:47:08,714 --> 00:47:10,048
"Dear Ishmael...

365
00:47:11,133 --> 00:47:13,677
"... I can't think of anything more painful...

366
00:47:14,219 --> 00:47:16,430
"... than writing this letter to you.

367
00:47:17,806 --> 00:47:21,310
"I feel I have to tell you the truth. "

368
00:47:50,172 --> 00:47:54,259
I know it's late. I went by the lighthouse
and I found a report that stated that...

369
00:47:54,343 --> 00:47:58,930
Just came across some information.
It may be relevant to Kazuo's case.

370
00:48:00,766 --> 00:48:04,227
...a giant freighter passed through
at the exact time that Carl died.

371
00:48:04,519 --> 00:48:07,272
I think it's something
that should have been discussed.

372
00:48:11,318 --> 00:48:12,694
I love you.

373
00:48:38,178 --> 00:48:39,638
Not just Hawaii.

374
00:48:40,055 --> 00:48:44,101
They're attacking all over the Pacific.
The whole fleet's destroyed.

375
00:48:46,436 --> 00:48:51,399
The FBl's in Seattle arresting Jap traitors.
Spies and everything.

376
00:48:52,901 --> 00:48:55,821
The defense commissioner
reckons anything can happen.

377
00:48:56,321 --> 00:48:58,073
There'll be a blackout.

378
00:48:59,366 --> 00:49:01,618
These people are our neighbors.

379
00:49:01,701 --> 00:49:04,579
Make sure you paper up your windows...

380
00:49:05,080 --> 00:49:06,915
...so the Japs won't find us.

381
00:49:06,998 --> 00:49:09,751
They've sent their sons into the U.S. army.

382
00:49:11,628 --> 00:49:13,463
They're no more an enemy than...

383
00:49:13,547 --> 00:49:18,134
...our fellow islanders of German
or Italian descent.

384
00:49:18,677 --> 00:49:20,220
You get the message?

385
00:49:20,428 --> 00:49:22,097
Mr. Lamberson?

386
00:49:24,850 --> 00:49:26,309
We get the message.

387
00:49:27,185 --> 00:49:31,147
Let us live that when it is over we can
look each other in the eye and know...

388
00:49:31,815 --> 00:49:33,900
...that we have acted honorably.

389
00:49:44,578 --> 00:49:46,371
Set that for me, would you?

390
00:49:56,172 --> 00:49:57,882
"Let us live...

391
00:49:59,134 --> 00:50:00,969
"... that when it is over...

392
00:50:03,013 --> 00:50:05,015
"... we can look each other...

393
00:50:06,016 --> 00:50:07,350
"... in the eye...

394
00:50:09,060 --> 00:50:10,437
"... and know...

395
00:50:10,937 --> 00:50:12,564
"... that we...

396
00:50:12,981 --> 00:50:14,399
"... have acted...

397
00:50:14,733 --> 00:50:16,151
"... honorably."

398
00:50:19,779 --> 00:50:22,032
The FBI has arrested Mr. Shirasaki...

399
00:50:22,282 --> 00:50:24,909
...and his family can't leave their house.

400
00:50:27,162 --> 00:50:29,080
Everything will be all right.

401
00:50:30,624 --> 00:50:32,042
I promise.

402
00:50:55,690 --> 00:50:57,108
We are loyal.

403
00:50:58,026 --> 00:51:01,363
- It's for our defense.
- Everyone on the island has these things.

404
00:51:01,446 --> 00:51:04,866
They'll hold onto this stuff for a while
then ship it back to you.

405
00:51:04,949 --> 00:51:06,659
Nothing to worry about.

406
00:51:07,577 --> 00:51:09,371
You folks have been real polite.

407
00:51:09,454 --> 00:51:11,790
We'll be out of here in just a second.

408
00:51:12,499 --> 00:51:14,042
That's very nice.

409
00:51:14,751 --> 00:51:16,920
From the old country, it appears.

410
00:51:17,128 --> 00:51:19,089
Very high class.

411
00:51:21,758 --> 00:51:23,134
These are...

412
00:51:23,551 --> 00:51:25,220
...real nice things.

413
00:51:28,223 --> 00:51:30,392
They'll take special care of...

414
00:51:34,604 --> 00:51:37,065
...any old-country stuff we have to take.

415
00:51:58,753 --> 00:52:00,338
Strawberry Princess?

416
00:52:01,131 --> 00:52:03,341
You must've been flattered by that.

417
00:52:05,135 --> 00:52:07,554
Crawford, guess what was in the shed?

418
00:52:08,054 --> 00:52:09,347
Dynamite.

419
00:52:09,556 --> 00:52:11,266
Twenty-four sticks.

420
00:52:12,809 --> 00:52:14,561
That's for tree stumps...

421
00:52:14,644 --> 00:52:16,229
...for clearing land.

422
00:52:17,021 --> 00:52:18,940
Maybe, but this is still bad, you see.

423
00:52:19,023 --> 00:52:22,318
It's illegal contraband.
You're supposed to turn that in.

424
00:52:22,443 --> 00:52:25,154
We've gotta arrest you
and bring you to Seattle.

425
00:52:25,238 --> 00:52:29,158
We don't need those. Mr. Imada-san
is a class act, a real gentleman.

426
00:52:29,450 --> 00:52:32,537
You can't do this.
He's done nothing wrong!

427
00:52:32,620 --> 00:52:36,207
Best for an honest man
to clear his name for good.

428
00:52:37,792 --> 00:52:39,961
Excuse me, would you mind?

429
00:53:18,416 --> 00:53:20,084
Journalism is the facts.

430
00:53:20,168 --> 00:53:24,255
Which facts? You can't print them all.
Journalism is making choices.

431
00:53:24,881 --> 00:53:26,883
Culling out what's unimportant.

432
00:53:27,300 --> 00:53:29,218
You know what happens to Jap lovers?

433
00:53:29,302 --> 00:53:32,972
Jap lovers get their balls cut off
and shoved down their throats.

434
00:53:38,686 --> 00:53:40,605
Better watch your step.

435
00:53:45,443 --> 00:53:47,945
- It's unbelievable to me.
- I don't know, Mom.

436
00:53:48,029 --> 00:53:52,492
The PTA honors 23 women. Dad singles
out three names and they're all Japanese.

437
00:53:52,617 --> 00:53:54,494
That's not journalism. It's propaganda.

438
00:53:54,577 --> 00:53:57,288
- This is dangerous, Arthur.
- It'll blow over.

439
00:53:57,372 --> 00:53:59,082
Did you see the letters?

440
00:54:02,919 --> 00:54:05,838
"Seems like you're favoring the Japs, Art.

441
00:54:06,672 --> 00:54:09,675
"Your newspaper's an insult
to all white Americans.

442
00:54:09,884 --> 00:54:12,929
- "Please cancel my subscription."
- What are you gonna do?

443
00:54:13,012 --> 00:54:14,514
Send him a refund.

444
00:54:16,182 --> 00:54:19,018
What happened to the Petersen ad
I put together?

445
00:54:19,560 --> 00:54:20,937
They pulled out.

446
00:54:21,396 --> 00:54:23,064
So did the gas station...

447
00:54:23,147 --> 00:54:25,441
...and Larson, and the cafe.

448
00:54:27,735 --> 00:54:28,861
What now?

449
00:54:35,868 --> 00:54:38,329
Print four pages instead of eight.

450
00:55:04,021 --> 00:55:08,109
"Please tell Sumiko to help her mother
with the garden work.

451
00:55:11,571 --> 00:55:14,282
"We are digging trenches
for a water system.

452
00:55:20,204 --> 00:55:24,083
"I am folding and ironing clothing
in the laundry."

453
00:55:25,084 --> 00:55:27,879
The hajukin,
they are no better than animals!

454
00:55:28,004 --> 00:55:29,422
Not all of them.

455
00:55:33,926 --> 00:55:35,386
How would you know?

456
00:55:36,137 --> 00:55:40,141
- I live here among them. So do you!
- You speak with great assurance.

457
00:55:42,018 --> 00:55:44,020
The words fly from your mouth.

458
00:55:44,270 --> 00:55:46,355
I don't care what you say.

459
00:55:46,522 --> 00:55:49,901
Do you hear me?
I don't want to be Japanese!

460
00:55:57,408 --> 00:55:58,784
Marry me, Hatsue.

461
00:56:04,916 --> 00:56:06,167
Please say yes.

462
00:56:06,250 --> 00:56:07,793
We'll leave here.

463
00:56:08,210 --> 00:56:09,837
Are you crazy?

464
00:56:11,213 --> 00:56:13,090
I want you to marry me.

465
01:04:22,537 --> 01:04:25,332
So, Dr. Whitman, sir, you found...

466
01:04:26,625 --> 01:04:28,418
...the blood on the gaff...

467
01:04:29,294 --> 01:04:31,421
...was not fish blood at all.

468
01:04:32,297 --> 01:04:34,257
It was human, yes?

469
01:04:35,383 --> 01:04:38,678
- Type B positive.
- Carl Heine's type.

470
01:04:39,721 --> 01:04:43,391
Yes, but you can't say with any certainty
that the blood was his.

471
01:04:43,892 --> 01:04:45,894
No, but as I say the...

472
01:04:46,102 --> 01:04:47,687
...type is rare.

473
01:04:47,896 --> 01:04:50,732
Ten percent of Caucasian males.
Whereas the...

474
01:04:51,149 --> 01:04:54,444
- ... defendant is type O.
- Yes, sir, you told us.

475
01:04:55,529 --> 01:04:58,782
No one is contesting that.
But you also told us that...

476
01:04:58,907 --> 01:05:01,993
...you scraped the dry blood
from the handle of the gaff.

477
01:05:04,871 --> 01:05:07,540
An object was propelled against....

478
01:05:07,624 --> 01:05:10,126
...found on Carl Heine's boat....

479
01:05:10,418 --> 01:05:12,087
But, the strange thing is....

480
01:05:12,170 --> 01:05:13,838
You asked me to explain it...

481
01:05:16,091 --> 01:05:19,970
The State calls Mrs. Susan Marie Heine.

482
01:05:49,165 --> 01:05:53,503
Can you think back for me
to the morning of September 8?

483
01:05:54,004 --> 01:05:56,881
The morning after your husband...

484
01:05:58,008 --> 01:06:00,260
...purchased the Jurgensen farm.

485
01:06:02,470 --> 01:06:05,432
One week before his death.

486
01:06:50,477 --> 01:06:54,647
Did the defendant come calling that day
to speak to your husband?

487
01:07:07,744 --> 01:07:09,204
It's no big deal.

488
01:07:10,789 --> 01:07:12,248
It's a long story.

489
01:07:14,000 --> 01:07:16,211
He wants to buy seven of Ole's acres.

490
01:07:16,294 --> 01:07:18,087
The ones his family had.

491
01:07:19,464 --> 01:07:21,925
You know that thing
my mother talks about?

492
01:07:22,008 --> 01:07:24,886
Had a feeling it was that.
What did you tell him?

493
01:07:24,969 --> 01:07:28,181
What could I tell him?
There's my mother to think about.

494
01:07:31,309 --> 01:07:32,602
I said I'd...

495
01:07:32,894 --> 01:07:35,522
...think it over, and have a talk with you.

496
01:07:36,314 --> 01:07:38,233
He go away angry?

497
01:07:40,235 --> 01:07:44,405
- I couldn't tell. You can't read Japs.
- Don't say that.

498
01:07:45,073 --> 01:07:47,742
You don't mean that. You fished together.

499
01:07:48,201 --> 01:07:49,911
You and he were friends.

500
01:07:51,746 --> 01:07:53,373
We were kids then.

501
01:08:16,437 --> 01:08:18,940
So your husband said he'd think it over.

