...to believe he might...

504
01:08:24,821 --> 01:08:26,948
Well, I wouldn't say encouraged.

505
01:08:28,283 --> 01:08:30,285
But he didn't say no, did he?

506
01:08:30,535 --> 01:08:32,745
He didn't say no hope existed.

507
01:08:33,538 --> 01:08:35,039
Not in those words.

508
01:08:36,332 --> 01:08:39,502
So, the defendant was encouraged to hope.

509
01:08:44,424 --> 01:08:48,678
How could anyone know what he hopes for
or anything else he's thinking?

510
01:08:50,179 --> 01:08:52,140
But, Mrs. Heine...

511
01:08:53,891 --> 01:08:55,560
...you really think that's fair?

512
01:08:55,643 --> 01:08:59,689
- Objection. That's totally irrelevant.
- There's nothing more relevant!

513
01:08:59,772 --> 01:09:01,649
You know that as well as anybody.

514
01:09:01,774 --> 01:09:03,443
Gentlemen, please!

515
01:09:03,860 --> 01:09:05,320
Back to your corners.

516
01:09:05,403 --> 01:09:09,032
Mrs. Heine, I'm very sorry
for this little interruption.

517
01:09:10,825 --> 01:09:12,410
No further questions.

518
01:09:12,744 --> 01:09:15,580
Thank you, Mrs. Heine.
You may step down.

519
01:09:18,124 --> 01:09:20,668
The State rests, Your Honor.

520
01:09:22,712 --> 01:09:24,797
Very well. Mr. Gudmundsson...

521
01:09:25,006 --> 01:09:27,592
...the defense may call its first witness.

522
01:09:28,634 --> 01:09:32,055
The defense calls Mrs. Hatsue Miyamoto.

523
01:09:45,777 --> 01:09:47,987
My husband came home excited.

524
01:09:49,030 --> 01:09:51,199
He woke me with the news.

525
01:09:51,741 --> 01:09:55,244
He told me he helped Carl at sea...

526
01:09:56,704 --> 01:09:59,207
...and Carl had agreed to sell us the land.

527
01:10:00,249 --> 01:10:02,919
We started making plans right away.

528
01:10:05,004 --> 01:10:09,050
When did you first learn
that Carl Heine had drowned?

529
01:10:13,137 --> 01:10:14,889
1:00 that afternoon...

530
01:10:15,348 --> 01:10:17,475
...from a clerk at Petersen's.

531
01:10:27,276 --> 01:10:29,529
- What is it?
- Carl Heine's dead.

532
01:10:29,612 --> 01:10:31,823
It's all over the island.

533
01:10:32,782 --> 01:10:36,410
- What do you mean?
- He drowned. They found him in his net.

534
01:10:37,495 --> 01:10:41,415
- Poor Susan Marie and those kids.
- I can't believe it.

535
01:10:49,090 --> 01:10:51,759
Gotta get to the boat, replace that battery.

536
01:10:52,510 --> 01:10:55,930
- What are you talking about?
- I was on his boat last night, remember?

537
01:10:56,389 --> 01:10:58,558
But you were helping him. Tell the sheriff.

538
01:10:58,641 --> 01:11:00,017
Are you kidding?

539
01:11:00,643 --> 01:11:02,353
You think they're gonna believe me?

540
01:11:02,436 --> 01:11:04,146
It's the truth, isn't it?

541
01:11:04,313 --> 01:11:06,941
That's right. Let'sjust leave it at that.

542
01:11:16,325 --> 01:11:20,413
Your husband came home agitated
after being at sea with the deceased?

543
01:11:22,790 --> 01:11:24,292
I said "excited"...

544
01:11:24,875 --> 01:11:26,294
...not "agitated."

545
01:11:26,711 --> 01:11:29,380
He was excited in the sense
of being overjoyed.

546
01:11:29,463 --> 01:11:31,132
You were...

547
01:11:32,091 --> 01:11:34,969
...overjoyed yourself to hear the news?

548
01:11:36,929 --> 01:11:38,848
Happy for him, and relieved.

549
01:11:40,933 --> 01:11:43,936
So then you and your husband,
you must've called...

550
01:11:45,438 --> 01:11:49,025
...friends and relatives to tell them
the happy news, yes?

551
01:11:50,568 --> 01:11:51,944
No.

552
01:11:53,863 --> 01:11:55,281
Really?

553
01:11:57,825 --> 01:12:00,828
You didn't call your family
about starting a new life?

554
01:12:00,911 --> 01:12:04,915
Your husband never tells his family
the family honor's been vindicated?

555
01:12:07,877 --> 01:12:09,962
We decided not to tell anyone...

556
01:12:10,421 --> 01:12:13,883
...until we signed papers
in case something went wrong.

557
01:12:17,303 --> 01:12:18,804
Then something did.

558
01:12:20,264 --> 01:12:22,641
Carl Heine was found dead...

559
01:12:24,435 --> 01:12:26,187
...with his head crushed.

560
01:12:29,190 --> 01:12:31,525
And then, what was there to call about?

561
01:12:31,609 --> 01:12:33,569
Everything was up in the air.

562
01:12:36,864 --> 01:12:38,532
"Up in the air."

563
01:12:39,617 --> 01:12:41,285
Was that your reaction?

564
01:12:41,994 --> 01:12:43,829
So, apart from your concern...

565
01:12:43,913 --> 01:12:46,957
...about a land deal evaporating,
what was your reaction...

566
01:12:47,041 --> 01:12:48,876
...to the news that a husband...

567
01:12:48,959 --> 01:12:52,963
...and father to small children was dead
with his skull bashed in?

568
01:12:54,673 --> 01:12:58,219
If you mean to imply
that we didn't care about Carl's death...

569
01:12:58,803 --> 01:13:01,555
...that is wrong and insulting.

570
01:13:02,681 --> 01:13:03,933
I see.

571
01:13:05,309 --> 01:13:07,269
Did it occur to you to come forward...

572
01:13:07,353 --> 01:13:10,815
...and tell Sheriff Moran
about the encounter in the fog?

573
01:13:10,898 --> 01:13:12,942
The dead battery, was it?

574
01:13:14,318 --> 01:13:15,861
We discussed that...

575
01:13:17,071 --> 01:13:18,697
...and decided not to.

576
01:13:19,240 --> 01:13:20,574
Why not?

577
01:13:23,035 --> 01:13:24,829
Because things looked bad.

578
01:13:25,121 --> 01:13:26,330
Very bad!

579
01:13:26,956 --> 01:13:28,874
Kazuo and I knew that.

580
01:13:29,250 --> 01:13:32,628
We thought he could end up here
on trial for murder.

581
01:13:33,128 --> 01:13:35,631
And that's exactly what has happened.

582
01:13:38,759 --> 01:13:43,305
But if truth was on your side,
whatever were you worried about?

583
01:13:45,599 --> 01:13:46,809
Trials...

584
01:13:47,309 --> 01:13:49,270
...aren't only about truth...

585
01:13:50,396 --> 01:13:52,898
- ... even though they should be.
- You hid the truth...

586
01:13:52,982 --> 01:13:55,401
...deliberately. You lied, didn't you?

587
01:13:56,068 --> 01:13:58,362
Coming forward seemed like a mistake.

588
01:13:58,445 --> 01:14:01,949
Doesn't it seem to you
that your mistake was in being deceitful...

589
01:14:02,032 --> 01:14:06,287
...and deliberately concealing information
during a sheriff's investigation?

590
01:14:09,874 --> 01:14:11,917
It seems human to me.

591
01:14:13,502 --> 01:14:16,964
I suppose you mean
that this somehow excuses your lies?

592
01:14:23,220 --> 01:14:24,597
I don't know.

593
01:14:27,933 --> 01:14:29,560
I don't understand.

594
01:14:29,977 --> 01:14:32,146
I'm completely at a loss.

595
01:14:33,897 --> 01:14:37,151
How on earth can you expect
any of us to believe you now?

596
01:14:37,276 --> 01:14:40,029
- Question withdrawn, Your Honor.
- Wait a minute!

597
01:14:40,112 --> 01:14:42,906
- I haven't had a chance.
- No further questions.

598
01:14:43,616 --> 01:14:45,534
That's enough, Mrs. Miyamoto.

599
01:14:45,618 --> 01:14:47,119
Not another word.

600
01:14:48,370 --> 01:14:52,416
The fact that you wish to give
Mr. Hooks a piece of your mind...

601
01:14:52,833 --> 01:14:54,793
...that just isn't allowed.

602
01:14:56,962 --> 01:14:58,172
Very well.

603
01:14:58,297 --> 01:15:00,549
Mr. Gudmundsson, will you redirect...

604
01:15:03,844 --> 01:15:06,764
Under the circumstances,
we will adjourn early.

605
01:15:07,264 --> 01:15:09,224
9:30 tomorrow.

606
01:16:49,908 --> 01:16:52,202
This is a very fine car.

607
01:16:52,494 --> 01:16:54,663
Much better than the new ones.

608
01:16:55,539 --> 01:16:57,499
Well, it was my father's.

609
01:16:58,458 --> 01:17:00,294
He was a good man.

610
01:17:04,131 --> 01:17:07,926
I know it's caused you trouble,
but the snow's beautiful, isn't it?

611
01:17:09,094 --> 01:17:11,388
Yes, very beautiful.

612
01:17:18,061 --> 01:17:20,022
This trial is unfair.

613
01:17:20,606 --> 01:17:23,775
Your father would have written
about that in his paper.

614
01:17:24,234 --> 01:17:25,944
What would he have said?

615
01:17:27,154 --> 01:17:28,989
How this trial is wrong!

616
01:17:29,239 --> 01:17:31,325
The whole thing is unfair!

617
01:17:31,658 --> 01:17:34,411
Sometimes I think unfairness is...

618
01:17:36,121 --> 01:17:37,539
...a part of things.

619
01:17:38,874 --> 01:17:42,669
I'm not talking about the whole universe.
I'm talking about people.

620
01:17:43,378 --> 01:17:46,089
The coroner, that prosecutor.

621
01:17:49,676 --> 01:17:51,386
You could do something to help.

622
01:17:51,470 --> 01:17:53,138
Is that what you think?

623
01:17:56,975 --> 01:17:59,061
Maybe I should write an article.

624
01:18:01,563 --> 01:18:03,231
About unfairness.

625
01:18:04,941 --> 01:18:07,944
About all the unfair things
people do to each other.

626
01:20:09,983 --> 01:20:12,027
Excuse me, Mrs. Chambers.

627
01:20:13,403 --> 01:20:17,073
The Japanese people of the island
are saddened by this loss.

628
01:20:18,074 --> 01:20:22,871
Your husband was a man of great
fairness and compassion for others.

629
01:20:23,246 --> 01:20:25,624
A friend to us and to all people.

630
01:20:26,875 --> 01:20:30,378
We know you will follow
in his footsteps, Ishmael...

631
01:20:30,795 --> 01:20:32,547
...and honor his legacy.

632
01:20:34,007 --> 01:20:35,467
Thank you.

633
01:21:06,081 --> 01:21:07,874
You should stay the night.

634
01:21:08,375 --> 01:21:11,670
- Don't drive back through this.
- I've got an early start.

635
01:21:21,137 --> 01:21:23,515
This room is full of ghosts, isn't it?

636
01:21:27,185 --> 01:21:29,604
I hate to see you this way.

637
01:21:30,689 --> 01:21:32,524
I don't know what you mean.

638
01:21:33,358 --> 01:21:35,235
She's married, Ishmael.

639
01:21:40,156 --> 01:21:43,993
Look, it's awfully cold in here.
Let's talk in the kitchen.

640
01:21:44,494 --> 01:21:46,663
I don't wanna talk about anything.

641
01:21:47,038 --> 01:21:50,875
- You're just like your father.
- I'm not just like my father!

642
01:21:50,959 --> 01:21:53,670
I know everyone wishes I was.
When they look at me...

643
01:21:53,753 --> 01:21:57,590
...I can hear them thinking,
"He's only half the man his father was."

644
01:21:59,968 --> 01:22:02,846
I was only going to say
he never minded the cold.

645
01:22:09,477 --> 01:22:12,021
It's not such a terrible thing...

646
01:22:13,106 --> 01:22:14,941
...being your father's son.

647
01:24:44,549 --> 01:24:46,718
Pardon us, Your Majesty.

648
01:24:50,221 --> 01:24:52,140
Who's your lover boy?

649
01:24:54,392 --> 01:24:55,935
Give it back!

650
01:25:13,619 --> 01:25:17,373
Does this explain your eagerness
to walk in the woods every day?

651
01:25:21,544 --> 01:25:22,837
Does it?

652
01:25:23,796 --> 01:25:25,214
Answer me!

653
01:25:46,194 --> 01:25:47,570
"Dear Ishmael...

654
01:25:50,573 --> 01:25:53,117
"... I can't think of anything more painful...

655
01:25:53,659 --> 01:25:55,953
"... than writing this letter to you.

656
01:25:57,205 --> 01:26:00,583
"I feel I have to tell you the truth.

657
01:26:02,210 --> 01:26:04,921
"When we met the last time
in the cedar tree...

658
01:26:06,672 --> 01:26:09,342
"... and I felt your body
move against mine...

659
01:26:12,929 --> 01:26:15,556
"... and I felt your body
move against mine...

660
01:26:17,808 --> 01:26:19,685
"... I knew with certainty...

661
01:26:21,020 --> 01:26:22,980
"... that everything was wrong.

662
01:26:24,232 --> 01:26:27,026
"I knew we could never be right together...

663
01:26:27,735 --> 01:26:30,655
"... and that soon
I would have to tell you so.

664
01:26:32,531 --> 01:26:34,033
"And now...

665
01:26:34,533 --> 01:26:36,160
"... with this letter...

666
01:26:37,078 --> 01:26:38,913
"... I am telling you.

667
01:26:53,594 --> 01:26:56,389
"This is the last time I'll write to you.

668
01:26:58,015 --> 01:26:59,976
"I'm not yours anymore.

669
01:27:03,270 --> 01:27:05,106
"I don't love you, Ishmael.

670
01:27:08,025 --> 01:27:10,611
"I can think of
no more honest way to say it.

671
01:27:12,196 --> 01:27:14,365
"When I heard your heart beating...

672
01:27:15,533 --> 01:27:17,493
"... as we lay together...

673
01:27:17,660 --> 01:27:21,038
"... I felt closer to you
than I had ever been to anyone.

674
01:27:23,708 --> 01:27:25,167
"And I knew...

675
01:27:26,752 --> 01:27:28,963
"... when I heard your heart beating...

676
01:27:29,088 --> 01:27:30,798
"... it could not last forever.

677
01:27:30,881 --> 01:27:33,592
"This is the last time I'll write to you.

678
01:27:33,676 --> 01:27:37,638
"I knew with certainty
that everything was wrong.

679
01:27:38,097 --> 01:27:39,432
"I loved you...

680
01:27:40,266 --> 01:27:43,144
"... and I didn't love you
at the same moment.

681
01:27:45,896 --> 01:27:48,482
"I can think of
no more honest way to say it.

682
01:27:53,279 --> 01:27:55,030
"I don't love you, Ishmael.

683
01:27:57,199 --> 01:28:00,828
"I knew it. I can think of
no more honest way to say it.

684
01:28:01,120 --> 01:28:03,080
"I loved you...

685
01:28:03,497 --> 01:28:06,500
"... and I didn't love you
at the same moment.

686
01:28:09,920 --> 01:28:12,465
"I'm going to move on with my life...

687
01:28:13,215 --> 01:28:15,092
"... as best I can.

688
01:28:16,510 --> 01:28:18,596
"And I hope that you will, too.

689
01:28:26,604 --> 01:28:28,522
"I don't love you, Ishmael.

690
01:28:32,067 --> 01:28:34,653
"I can think of
no more honest way to say it.

691
01:28:34,737 --> 01:28:36,655
"Whenever we were together...

692
01:28:37,573 --> 01:28:39,283
"... I knew it.

693
01:28:44,997 --> 01:28:46,290
"I loved you...

694
01:28:47,917 --> 01:28:50,669
"... and I didn't love you
at the same moment.

695
01:29:46,308 --> 01:29:47,559
"You must live.

696
01:29:55,943 --> 01:29:57,861
"I must say good-bye to you.

697
01:30:03,158 --> 01:30:06,537
"I know you will do great things
in this world.

698
01:30:08,330 --> 01:30:10,874
"You have a gentle heart.

699
01:30:13,627 --> 01:30:15,212
"A good heart.

700
01:30:18,507 --> 01:30:20,759
"I will never forget you...

701
01:30:23,846 --> 01:30:27,224
"... and the time we spent together. "

702
01:30:36,233 --> 01:30:37,651
Scissors.

703
01:30:41,613 --> 01:30:43,532
Retractor.

704
01:30:44,992 --> 01:30:46,535
Reticular clamp.

705
01:30:48,078 --> 01:30:50,247
Fuckin' Jap bitch.

706
01:31:57,523 --> 01:31:59,900
- They're sending you to Europe?
- I think so.

707
01:31:59,983 --> 01:32:02,319
Why did you have to volunteer?

708
01:32:16,500 --> 01:32:18,252
They'll hear everything.

709
01:32:20,295 --> 01:32:22,256
Wouldn't some music be nice?

710
01:33:20,022 --> 01:33:22,190
Have you ever done this before?

711
01:33:22,482 --> 01:33:23,942
Never.

712
01:33:24,359 --> 01:33:26,278
You're my only.

713
01:34:00,103 --> 01:34:02,731
Do you swear to tell the truth,
the whole truth...

714
01:34:02,814 --> 01:34:05,525
...and nothing but the truth,
so help you God?

715
01:34:05,692 --> 01:34:06,902
I do.

716
01:34:07,194 --> 01:34:10,030
I heard an air horn
and saw a lantern in the fog.

717
01:34:10,113 --> 01:34:11,281
That you, Miyamoto?

718
01:34:11,364 --> 01:34:13,033
And another one in Carl's hand.

719
01:34:13,116 --> 01:34:14,576
What's up, Carl?

720
01:34:16,620 --> 01:34:18,789
Both my batteries are drawn down.

721
01:34:19,498 --> 01:34:21,458
The generator belts were loose.

722
01:34:21,541 --> 01:34:24,419
Lantern and air horn's all I got.
I'm dead here.

723
01:34:26,004 --> 01:34:27,297
No problem.

724
01:34:28,173 --> 01:34:30,967
We'll pull one of my batteries
and get you started.

725
01:34:32,677 --> 01:34:36,515
That thing's big, but it'll fit
if I bang the flange out of the way.

726
01:34:36,681 --> 01:34:38,725
We can use this to hammer with.

727
01:34:39,059 --> 01:34:42,395
I can't imagine why you kept this story
from the sheriff.

728
01:34:42,479 --> 01:34:43,647
Why?

729
01:34:44,064 --> 01:34:45,774
I didn't have a lawyer.

730
01:34:46,107 --> 01:34:49,611
Even after you had an attorney,
you still claimed to know nothing.

731
01:34:49,694 --> 01:34:51,279
You claim not to have seen Carl.

732
01:34:51,363 --> 01:34:53,573
- Am I correct?
- Yes, initially.

733
01:34:57,619 --> 01:34:58,954
"Initially."

734
01:34:59,496 --> 01:35:02,332
That's an interesting word.
You'd been arrested.

735
01:35:02,749 --> 01:35:05,460
You had a lawyer.
You still claimed ignorance.

736
01:35:05,544 --> 01:35:08,547
I should've told everything right away.

737
01:35:08,630 --> 01:35:10,549
"Should've told everything."

738
01:35:11,466 --> 01:35:13,802
Meaning you should've told the truth.

739
01:35:14,594 --> 01:35:16,304
But is that the truth?

740
01:35:17,681 --> 01:35:20,183
The whole truth? Is it?

741
01:35:21,226 --> 01:35:23,270
You don't wanna hear the whole truth.

742
01:35:23,562 --> 01:35:25,438
Why don't you try me?

743
01:35:30,485 --> 01:35:33,029
The whole truth is, I wanted to kill him.

744
01:35:35,532 --> 01:35:37,200
But did you?

745
01:35:45,417 --> 01:35:46,918
Nothing to say?

746
01:36:16,614 --> 01:36:18,825
It'll take me a while to charge up.

747
01:36:20,744 --> 01:36:21,995
We'll catch up on the dock.

748
01:36:22,078 --> 01:36:23,788
Nothing to say?

749
01:36:25,665 --> 01:36:29,544
- I didn't know that was a question.
- My apologies. Do you regret...

750
01:36:29,627 --> 01:36:32,047
- ... not telling the truth?
- I have told the truth.

751
01:36:32,130 --> 01:36:35,633
You mean this morning.
The battery story. That one is the truth?

752
01:36:35,717 --> 01:36:37,927
- That's a question, sir.
- Yes.

753
01:36:39,346 --> 01:36:41,348
And I told it long before this morning.

754
01:36:41,431 --> 01:36:44,100
You said in your testimony...

755
01:36:45,018 --> 01:36:46,144
...that...

756
01:36:46,394 --> 01:36:49,898
..."I slept until 1:30
when my wife woke me with the news.

757
01:36:50,315 --> 01:36:53,693
"We talked for a while,
then I went straight to my boat."

758
01:36:54,569 --> 01:36:56,780
You didn't go anywhere else
but to your boat.

759
01:36:56,863 --> 01:36:58,656
- Is that the truth?
- Yes.

760
01:36:59,574 --> 01:37:03,578
The sheriff found two batteries
in your well.

761
01:37:03,703 --> 01:37:06,372
If, as you claim, you left one with Carl...

762
01:37:06,831 --> 01:37:08,291
...how's that possible?

763
01:37:08,374 --> 01:37:10,335
I had a spare battery in my shed.

764
01:37:10,418 --> 01:37:13,254
I brought it down and put it in
before the sheriff came.

765
01:37:13,338 --> 01:37:15,882
Conveniently, in your shed.

766
01:37:17,217 --> 01:37:20,637
Why does the battery story change
every time a new question's raised?

767
01:37:20,720 --> 01:37:24,224
You asked me if I went straight
to the boat. I did, with the battery.

768
01:37:24,307 --> 01:37:29,229
And the new line? Was that in your shed?
You have a regular chandlery in there?

769
01:37:29,395 --> 01:37:32,273
You have no answer,
you sit in silence with no expression?

770
01:37:32,357 --> 01:37:34,943
You're a hard man to trust, sir.

771
01:37:35,026 --> 01:37:36,277
Objection!

772
01:37:36,361 --> 01:37:37,737
Sustained.

773
01:37:38,321 --> 01:37:40,406
You know better than that.

774
01:37:40,865 --> 01:37:44,452
Either ask questions that count
for something or sit down.

775
01:37:50,458 --> 01:37:52,001
Shame on you.

776
01:37:56,089 --> 01:37:58,049
No further questions.

777
01:38:07,016 --> 01:38:09,894
Believing that Etta Heine's son...

778
01:38:10,436 --> 01:38:14,232
...would never sell him the land,
land that in his mind...

779
01:38:15,108 --> 01:38:16,901
...belonged to his family.

780
01:38:17,527 --> 01:38:19,696
His only chance to get that land...

781
01:38:19,779 --> 01:38:22,282
...would be to eliminate Carl Heine.

782
01:38:22,448 --> 01:38:27,036
Thus believing that cold-blooded murder
was justified...

783
01:38:27,996 --> 01:38:29,372
...he trailed Carl.

784
01:38:29,497 --> 01:38:34,168
He strikes the treacherous blow
he'd been trained to strike by his father.

785
01:38:34,502 --> 01:38:36,254
After a series of lies...

786
01:38:38,131 --> 01:38:40,717
...the defendant at last admits
he was there...

787
01:38:40,800 --> 01:38:43,219
...alone on the boat in the fog.

788
01:38:44,137 --> 01:38:47,765
Carl Heine's blood on his fishing gaff.

789
01:38:48,808 --> 01:38:50,143
Seven acres.

790
01:38:52,103 --> 01:38:55,648
I just wonder what you'd pay for 'em.
Just curious, is all.

791
01:38:55,773 --> 01:38:57,734
What are you selling 'em for?

792
01:38:57,900 --> 01:38:59,611
Did I say I was sellin'?

793
01:39:00,320 --> 01:39:01,738
If I was, I guess I'd have to...

794
01:39:01,821 --> 01:39:05,992
...figure you want 'em real bad.
I ought to charge a small fortune, maybe.

795
01:39:16,085 --> 01:39:19,797
All right, I'm sorry about it, okay?
About the whole damn mess.

796
01:39:26,054 --> 01:39:27,513
$1,200 an acre.

797
01:39:31,809 --> 01:39:34,729
That's what I paid Ole.
You got no choice on that.

798
01:39:36,689 --> 01:39:38,399
We'll sign off tomorrow.

799
01:39:38,566 --> 01:39:40,818
Look clearly at the defendant.

800
01:39:41,861 --> 01:39:44,822
See the truth self-evident in him...

801
01:39:45,406 --> 01:39:47,742
...and in the facts of this case.

802
01:39:49,118 --> 01:39:51,662
Look into his eyes, ladies and gentlemen.

803
01:39:53,623 --> 01:39:55,541
Consider his face.

804
01:39:56,876 --> 01:39:58,461
Ask yourself...

805
01:40:02,757 --> 01:40:04,342
...each one of you:

806
01:40:08,513 --> 01:40:11,682
"What is my duty as a citizen
of this community?

807
01:40:14,727 --> 01:40:16,104
"Of this country?

808
01:40:19,107 --> 01:40:20,441
"As an American?"

809
01:40:40,962 --> 01:40:44,632
There's no evidence of anger at Carl,
much less rage...

810
01:40:45,299 --> 01:40:47,218
...much less murderous rage.

811
01:40:48,344 --> 01:40:50,972
No reason for premeditation.

812
01:40:51,389 --> 01:40:53,808
No evidence of it anywhere.

813
01:40:55,476 --> 01:40:56,894
He had asked...

814
01:40:57,311 --> 01:41:01,899
...his childhood friend to sell him
some land. And Carl was considering it.

815
01:41:02,358 --> 01:41:04,569
Carl's own wife testified that...

816
01:41:04,819 --> 01:41:07,613
...her husband had not made up his mind.

817
01:41:09,949 --> 01:41:12,660
A strange moment to follow and kill a man.

818
01:41:13,161 --> 01:41:14,453
Don't you think?

819
01:41:14,537 --> 01:41:18,624
What Mr. Hooks asks you to believe
is that no proof is needed...

820
01:41:20,126 --> 01:41:22,670
...against a man who bombed Pearl Harbor.

821
01:41:25,798 --> 01:41:28,342
"Look at his face," the prosecutor said...

822
01:41:28,426 --> 01:41:31,137
...presuming that you will see
an enemy there.

823
01:41:31,387 --> 01:41:33,097
He's counting on you...

824
01:41:34,390 --> 01:41:37,894
...to remember this war
and to see Kazuo Miyamoto as...

825
01:41:38,519 --> 01:41:40,855
...somehow connected with it.

826
01:41:42,231 --> 01:41:43,524
Indeed he is!

827
01:41:44,525 --> 01:41:46,027
Let us recall that...

828
01:41:46,110 --> 01:41:49,614
...First Lieutenant Kazuo Miyamoto
is a much-decorated hero...

829
01:41:49,780 --> 01:41:51,741
...of the United States Army.

830
01:41:55,703 --> 01:41:57,246
Kazuo Miyamoto did...

831
01:41:57,914 --> 01:41:59,457
...one thing wrong.

832
01:42:01,250 --> 01:42:03,127
He wasn't certain he could trust us.

833
01:42:03,210 --> 01:42:06,756
He was afraid that he would be made
the victim of prejudice...

834
01:42:07,131 --> 01:42:09,342
...as Mr. Hooks, indeed...

835
01:42:10,301 --> 01:42:12,053
...is urging you to do.

836
01:42:13,679 --> 01:42:16,098
There's reason in his uncertainty.

837
01:42:16,641 --> 01:42:17,808
Why?

838
01:42:18,059 --> 01:42:20,686
Well, we sent him and his wife and...

839
01:42:21,103 --> 01:42:24,649
...thousands of Americans
to concentration camps.

840
01:42:25,191 --> 01:42:28,486
They lost their homes, their belongings...

841
01:42:29,654 --> 01:42:30,738
...everything.

842
01:42:30,821 --> 01:42:34,158
Should we now be unforgiving
of his mistrust?

843
01:42:41,374 --> 01:42:45,628
Our learned prosecutor
will have you do your duty as Americans.

844
01:42:45,961 --> 01:42:47,338
Proud Americans.

845
01:42:47,880 --> 01:42:50,466
Of course, you must! And if you do...

846
01:42:51,801 --> 01:42:54,470
...Kazuo Miyamoto has nothing to fear.
Because...

847
01:42:55,513 --> 01:42:59,517
...this great country is supposed
to be founded on a set of principles...

848
01:42:59,850 --> 01:43:01,352
...of fairness...

849
01:43:03,229 --> 01:43:06,816
...of equality and justice.
And if you are true...

850
01:43:09,068 --> 01:43:10,611
...to these principles...

851
01:43:10,694 --> 01:43:14,698
...you'll only convict a man
for what he's done, and not for who he is.

852
01:43:18,369 --> 01:43:20,079
I'm an old man.

853
01:43:21,122 --> 01:43:24,333
I don't walk so well anymore.
One of my eyes is close to useless.

854
01:43:24,417 --> 01:43:26,419
My life is drawing to a close.

855
01:43:27,044 --> 01:43:28,546
Why do I say this?

856
01:43:29,004 --> 01:43:33,342
I say this because it means
that I ponder matters...

857
01:43:34,135 --> 01:43:35,928
...in the light of death...

858
01:43:36,512 --> 01:43:39,181
...in a way that most of you do not.

859
01:43:40,099 --> 01:43:42,685
I feel like a traveler descended...

860
01:43:43,477 --> 01:43:47,148
...from Mars, astounded by what I see here.

861
01:43:47,606 --> 01:43:50,693
The same human frailty...

862
01:43:51,527 --> 01:43:54,071
...passed on from generation to generation.

863
01:43:54,155 --> 01:43:56,782
We hate one another.
We are the victims of...

864
01:43:57,825 --> 01:43:59,952
...irrational fears, of prejudice.

865
01:44:02,496 --> 01:44:03,914
You might think...

866
01:44:04,832 --> 01:44:08,169
...that this is a small trial in a small place.

867
01:44:11,714 --> 01:44:13,090
It isn't.

868
01:44:13,841 --> 01:44:16,635
Every once in a while,
somewhere in the world...

869
01:44:16,719 --> 01:44:19,263
...humanity goes on trial...

870
01:44:20,806 --> 01:44:22,349
...and integrity...

871
01:44:23,017 --> 01:44:24,476
...and decency.

872
01:44:25,686 --> 01:44:27,396
Every once in a while...

873
01:44:27,980 --> 01:44:31,108
...ordinary people just like you,
ladies and gentlemen...

874
01:44:31,192 --> 01:44:34,904
...get called on to give the report card
for the human race.

875
01:44:39,783 --> 01:44:41,744
In the name of humanity...

876
01:44:42,244 --> 01:44:44,288
...do your duty as jurors.

877
01:44:46,582 --> 01:44:49,501
Return this man to his wife and children.

878
01:44:50,461 --> 01:44:52,129
Set him free...

879
01:44:53,672 --> 01:44:55,215
...as you must.

880
01:45:34,213 --> 01:45:36,131
Good night, Mrs. Miyamoto.

881
01:46:28,892 --> 01:46:30,352
Please.

882
01:46:33,230 --> 01:46:35,482
I know you'll think this is crazy...

883
01:46:35,983 --> 01:46:38,193
...but all I want to do is hold you.

884
01:46:38,402 --> 01:46:42,364
I think that ifyou'll let me do that
just for a few seconds...

885
01:46:46,785 --> 01:46:48,954
...I can walk away...

886
01:46:49,538 --> 01:46:51,623
...and never speak to you again.

887
01:46:54,501 --> 01:46:56,545
Can you please look at me?

888
01:47:30,829 --> 01:47:32,748
I did a terrible thing.

889
01:47:34,458 --> 01:47:36,335
But you have to hear this.

890
01:47:36,460 --> 01:47:38,128
I can never touch you.

891
01:47:39,087 --> 01:47:40,631
You have to let go.

892
01:47:41,590 --> 01:47:43,550
That's the way things are.

893
01:47:51,975 --> 01:47:53,518
Things end, Ishmael.

894
01:47:56,396 --> 01:47:57,898
They do.

895
01:48:00,108 --> 01:48:01,777
You have to let go.

896
01:48:23,548 --> 01:48:26,593
I went by the lighthouse,
and I found a report that stated...

897
01:48:26,677 --> 01:48:31,723
...a freighter passed through
the Channel at the time of Carl's death.

898
01:48:32,599 --> 01:48:36,228
This is something that
should've been discussed at the trial.

899
01:48:36,687 --> 01:48:39,356
I can't believe I let you rope me into this.

900
01:48:39,648 --> 01:48:41,817
We've been over these boats
a dozen times.

901
01:48:41,900 --> 01:48:45,362
If there's a lantern on Carl's mast,
then Miyamoto's story's true.

902
01:48:45,445 --> 01:48:46,613
See?

903
01:48:46,947 --> 01:48:48,198
No lantern.

904
01:48:49,658 --> 01:48:50,784
What are those?

905
01:48:50,867 --> 01:48:54,079
- Nothing. Bits of twine.
- Bits of twine aren't nothing.

906
01:48:56,623 --> 01:48:59,209
Maybe somebody should
take a look at those.

907
01:49:04,297 --> 01:49:07,843
Don't touch anything up there.
It's still a crime scene, remember?

908
01:49:07,926 --> 01:49:10,554
Don't ever touch something
at a crime scene.

909
01:49:18,979 --> 01:49:22,190
Doesn't the phrase, "The jury's out,"
mean anything to you?

910
01:49:23,567 --> 01:49:25,402
They're lashings.

911
01:49:26,319 --> 01:49:28,655
Figure-eight lashings all cut through.

912
01:49:30,741 --> 01:49:32,409
And you know something?

913
01:49:32,659 --> 01:49:34,745
These stains here on the mast...

914
01:49:34,953 --> 01:49:36,663
...they could be blood.

915
01:49:38,540 --> 01:49:40,417
The cut on his hand.

916
01:49:41,710 --> 01:49:43,336
See this?

917
01:49:56,349 --> 01:49:58,268
I think you better come down here.

918
01:49:58,351 --> 01:50:01,813
- There's something you should see.
- What the hell is it now?

919
01:50:04,441 --> 01:50:06,651
- What?
- Take a look at this.

920
01:50:20,248 --> 01:50:21,791
This better be good.

921
01:50:22,792 --> 01:50:27,047
I can admit evidence if required
in the interest of justice.

922
01:50:27,881 --> 01:50:29,633
Only if it changes everything.

923
01:50:29,716 --> 01:50:31,551
Nels explained that to you?

924
01:50:32,594 --> 01:50:34,346
- Yes, he did.
- Very well then.

925
01:50:34,429 --> 01:50:37,140
About this second lantern
and the freighter.

926
01:50:37,224 --> 01:50:40,101
After Miyamoto left,
and Carl's engine was running...

927
01:50:40,185 --> 01:50:44,689
...he must have remembered the lantern,
so he climbs up to cut it down.

928
01:51:29,234 --> 01:51:34,197
Everything fits: the coast guard report,
the lanterns, the freighter's course...

929
01:51:34,280 --> 01:51:38,952
...the coffee cup, the time on Carl's watch
and Carl's blood on the fishing gaff.

930
01:51:39,244 --> 01:51:42,038
Your Honor,
that is the rankest speculation.

931
01:51:44,124 --> 01:51:45,333
Please, spare me.

932
01:51:45,417 --> 01:51:47,293
- With all due respect...
- You listen here!

933
01:51:47,377 --> 01:51:49,295
We're going to hear this theory out.

934
01:51:49,379 --> 01:51:52,424
If justice demands it,
we're gonna let the jury hear it...

935
01:51:52,507 --> 01:51:54,843
...just in case it might be the truth.

936
01:51:56,970 --> 01:52:00,473
- The head wound?
- We found a small fracture in the gunnel.

937
01:52:00,557 --> 01:52:02,976
- Just below the mast.
- Anything could've caused it.

938
01:52:03,059 --> 01:52:05,687
- Anything with human hair.
- Why?

939
01:52:11,151 --> 01:52:12,444
May I?

940
01:52:14,571 --> 01:52:16,614
This isn't a legal case.

941
01:52:16,698 --> 01:52:18,950
There's no way to prove any of this,
Your Honor.

942
01:52:19,033 --> 01:52:21,828
This certainly warrants a fresh look.

943
01:52:24,664 --> 01:52:26,416
I want to think about it.

944
01:52:36,009 --> 01:52:37,552
By the way...

945
01:52:37,927 --> 01:52:41,097
...this coast guard report,
when did you come across it?

946
01:52:44,476 --> 01:52:47,061
Was it today you went out
to the lighthouse?

947
01:52:51,357 --> 01:52:53,234
Day before yesterday.

948
01:52:58,198 --> 01:53:00,492
You're wondering why I held on to it.

949
01:53:00,575 --> 01:53:02,202
Perhaps I have some...

950
01:53:02,827 --> 01:53:03,953
...idea.

951
01:53:09,375 --> 01:53:11,419
Could it have anything to do...

952
01:53:15,131 --> 01:53:17,175
...with the way you look at her?

953
01:53:23,598 --> 01:53:25,558
It takes a rare thing...

954
01:53:26,392 --> 01:53:27,977
...a turning point...

955
01:53:28,144 --> 01:53:30,313
...to free oneself from any...

956
01:53:31,147 --> 01:53:34,108
...obsession. Be it prejudice or hate or...

957
01:53:35,068 --> 01:53:37,028
...even love.

958
01:53:39,322 --> 01:53:40,865
I had to, really.

959
01:53:44,118 --> 01:53:45,537
I had no choice.

960
01:53:47,539 --> 01:53:50,291
You're sounding
just a little like your father.

961
01:53:50,750 --> 01:53:53,253
Did I ever tell you how much I liked him?

962
01:53:58,967 --> 01:54:00,802
I keep thinking about Carl.

963
01:54:01,594 --> 01:54:03,346
How unfair it seems.

964
01:54:03,930 --> 01:54:05,974
An accident. Just like that.

965
01:54:07,600 --> 01:54:09,978
Things just bear down on us, I suppose.

966
01:54:11,104 --> 01:54:13,064
A freighter in the fog.

967
01:54:15,984 --> 01:54:17,902
Or a war.

968
01:54:22,782 --> 01:54:25,493
Accident rules every corner of the universe.

969
01:54:26,577 --> 01:54:28,288
Except maybe...

970
01:54:29,372 --> 01:54:31,624
...the chambers of the human heart.

971
01:55:55,500 --> 01:55:56,834
Morning, Horace.

972
01:55:57,001 --> 01:55:58,753
Reminds you of 1930, doesn't it?

973
01:55:58,836 --> 01:56:03,382
I believe you're thinking of 1929.

974
01:56:03,466 --> 01:56:05,009
Of course it was.

975
01:56:05,593 --> 01:56:07,512
Winter of '29.

976
01:56:32,286 --> 01:56:33,621
All rise.

977
01:56:33,871 --> 01:56:36,541
The Superior Court
of the State of Washington...

978
01:56:36,624 --> 01:56:39,502
...County of San Piedro, is now in session.

979
01:56:47,969 --> 01:56:49,554
Members of the jury:

980
01:56:50,054 --> 01:56:53,558
The court thanks you for your diligence
in the task you've performed...

981
01:56:53,641 --> 01:56:55,685
...under difficult circumstances.

982
01:56:55,768 --> 01:56:56,811
However...

983
01:56:56,894 --> 01:57:00,064
...in the light of the new forensic evidence
we have heard...

984
01:57:00,147 --> 01:57:03,359
...you are hereby discharged
from your responsibilities.

985
01:57:13,077 --> 01:57:14,120
Order.

986
01:57:58,456 --> 01:57:59,498
Order.

987
01:57:59,999 --> 01:58:01,792
You will resume your seats.

988
01:58:14,513 --> 01:58:15,848
Settle down.

989
01:58:19,810 --> 01:58:21,479
Let us not forget...

990
01:58:22,063 --> 01:58:25,066
...we have been considering the death
of one man...

991
01:58:25,649 --> 01:58:28,319
...as well as pondering the fate of another.

992
01:58:31,072 --> 01:58:33,074
Will the defendant please rise?

993
01:58:38,871 --> 01:58:40,289
Kazuo Miyamoto...

994
01:58:40,790 --> 01:58:42,625
...in the interest of justice...

995
01:58:42,708 --> 01:58:46,378
...the charges against you are dismissed.
You're free to go home.

996
02:00:36,030 --> 02:00:37,740
Can I hold you now?

997
02:00:51,462 --> 02:00:54,673
I'm so grateful for your gentle heart.

998
02:07:00,955 --> 02:07:03,041
Subtitles by SOFTITLER

